<font color="#FF0000">HI! DOC DEL, I'M BACK ON LINE.</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar  8  7:35:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Del,<br><br>
You know it is funny, but those most in denial were not there with us. It is also funny that many have opinions based upon theory, and they were not there with us.<br><br>
Being there is the one true thing that sets us apart from everyone else. No one can deny our experiences. They may find our renditions and stories uncomfortable, but they are absolutely true accounts of what happened. <br><br>
Sure, anyone can pick apart one event, one hour, minute or second, of anything. Add it all up from all of us, and you have something a whole lot different. Guess what we are really doing here. *Adding it all up.* I hope it scares the hell out of some people. It did me, and continues to do so. <br><br>
I also find it odd that for a society enthralled with violence in the media from Chain Saw Horror to 911, people have dificulty in accepting the horror of the truth. Maybe we should start a blood and guts post of the truth. I don't think the POV people would like it, and I don't really recommend it,  but I sure would like to drag some of the people here back there with us in time and take a few 122's and other assorted things right next to us. I am sure they would also not appreciate the bloated dead rats that floated by once in a while. Or the invasion of the millions of tiny frogs that would crunch under your feet. Or the leeches. Or the giant flying cockroaches. Or that little green snake that would send even charlie running in a panic. **Or experience the stuff about living and dead people that most of us have extraordinary difficulty in recollecting, much less writing down.** <br><br>
H.G. Wells, where are you when we most need you?<br><br>
Second guessing on how we &quot;should&quot; have fought or protested going or just being there is another habit of someone else's personal denial, or perhaps justification of what they did in the light of the truth of what we experienced. Instead of looking at things as fate, circumstance, or personal decisions, or the honest fact that some of us were just stuck with it and had no way out, some try to paint us as the offender.<br><br>
In our hooch we used to have slime mold races in the rainy season, just for fun. We used to bet on the winners. It was slow fun. Do you know how slow slime molds move? It sometimes took days. What a hell of a way to have to stretch out the only fun game in town. <br><br>
If that sounds a little disconnected, it was! I am sure someone will take a shot at it, though. HA!<br><br>
My mood is a little different right now, but I have been off line for a while.<br><br>
It is good to be back up.<br><br>
Arthur<br><br>

